nodes.bodyText:
I see. I didn't think it through. I think we can pass the cause to TimeoutScheduler like you suggested, but then should also pass the cause to TimeoutTask.run(cause)? That makes sure the cause is correct when the task runs.
// ClientContext
void cancel(Throwable cause) {
    scheduler.finishNow(cause);
}

@Nullable
Throwable cancellationCause() {
    return scheduler.cause(); // null when timeoutTask has not run
}

// TimeoutScheduler
void init(..., Throwable cause /* the initial cause */) { 
    eventLoop.schedule(() -> invokeTimeoutTask(cause),...);
}

void finishNow(Throwable cause) {
    // the scheduled task is cleared if not yet executed
    eventLoop.execute(() -> invokeTimeoutTask(cause));
}

void invokeTimeoutTask(Throwable cause) {
    ...
    timeoutTask.run(cause);
    this.cause = cause; // now we set the final cause. this cannot be changed because state=FINISHED
}
We can cancel handlers if cause not instanceof TimeoutException.

